The '''Grainger challenge''' is a scientific competition to find an economical way to [[water purification|remove]] [[arsenic]] from [[Arsenic contamination of groundwater|arsenic-contaminated groundwater]]. This competition is being funded by the [[United States National Academy of Engineering]] and the Grainger Foundation and is meant to help provide safe [[drinking water]] to countries such as [[Bangladesh]], [[India]], and [[Cambodia]].

In 2007, the winner of the Gold Award ($1,000,000) was [[Abul Hussam]], for his invention of the [[Sono arsenic filter]].  The Silver Award ($200,000) was awarded to [[Arup K Sengupta]] for his invention and implementation of [http://www.systematixusa.com/products/media/active_media/arsenx.htm ArsenX<sup>np</sup>] hybrid anion exchange (HAIX) resin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pfitzer |first=Kurt |title=Arsenic-removal system wins NAE award |url=http://www3.lehigh.edu/News/RCEASnews_story.asp?iNewsID=2013 |work=Arsenic-removal system wins NAE award |publisher=Lehigh University |accessdate=23 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927094830/http://www3.lehigh.edu/News/RCEASnews_story.asp?iNewsID=2013 |archivedate=27 September 2011 |df= }}</ref>  The Children's Safe Drinking Water Program at [[Procter & Gamble]] (P&G), Cincinnati, received the Bronze Award of US$ 100,000 for the [http://www.purwater.com/clean-drinking-water-for-the-world.html PUR™ Purifier of Water] coagulation and flocculation water treatment system.

