The '''Scottish School of Primary Care''' ('''SSPC''') is an organisation that co-ordinates a programme of research and training of [[primary care]] in [[Scotland]]. The School was launched in 2000.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/scots-launch-primary-care-school/20001809.article |title=Scots launch primary care school |work=[[The Pharmaceutical Journal]] |volume=264 |number=7100 |pages=868 |date=10 June 2000}}</ref> By 2007 there were 1700 people involved in this virtual organisation, including Scottish academics with an interest in primary care research and clinicians who have an involvement with research alongside their normal clinical work.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Primary care research networks in the United Kingdom |journal=[[BMJ]] |first1=Frank |last1=Sullivan |first2=Chris |last2=Butler |first3=Margaret |last3=Cupples |first4=Ann-Louise |last4=Kinmonth |date=24 May 2007 |volume=334 |doi=10.1136/bmj.39190.648785.80 |pages=1093}}</ref>

A programme of work at the school led to the publication of landmark paper on [[multimorbidity]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gponline.com/viewpoint-multimorbidity-its-challenge-general-practice/article/1131991 |title=Viewpoint - Multimorbidity and its challenge to general practice |first=John |last=Gilles |work=[[GP (magazine)|GP]] |date=15 May 2012 |accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>

In 2007, [[Frank Sullivan (medical doctor)|Frank Sullivan]] was appointed Director. In September 2015, [[John Gillies (medical doctor)|John Gillies]] took up the position of Depute Director.

