{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}
'''Standard of living in India''' varies from state to state. With one of the fastest growing economies in the [[world]], clocked at a [[Economic growth|growth rate]] of 7.6% in 2015, India is on its way to becoming a large and globally important [[consumer economy]]. According to Deutsche Bank Research, there are between 30 million and 300 million middle-class people in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbresearch.de/PROD/DBR_INTERNET_DE-PROD/PROD0000000000253735.pdf|title=The middle class in India |publisher=Deutsche Bank Research}}</ref> If current trends continue, India's share of world GDP will significantly increase from 7.3 in 2016 to 8.5 percent of the world share by 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2016/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=54&pr.y=8&sy=2016&ey=2020&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=534&s=PPPSH&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|publisher=}}</ref> In 2011, less than 22 percent of Indians lived under the global poverty line, nearly an 8 percent reduction from  29.8 percent just two years prior in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.worldbank.org/country/india|title=India - Data|work=data.worldbank.org}}</ref>

According to NCAER, India's middle class population would be 267 million in 2016. Further ahead, by 2025-26 the number of middle class households in India is likely to more than double from the 2015-16 levels to 113.8 million households or 547 million individuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-02-06/news/28424975_1_middle-class-households-applied-economic-research|title=India's middle class population to touch 267 million in 5 yrs|publisher=}}</ref> Another estimate put the Indian middle class as numbering 475 million people by 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ey.com/GL/en/Issues/Driving-growth/Middle-class-growth-in-emerging-markets---China-and-India-tomorrow-s-middle-classes |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090932/http://www.ey.com/GL/en/Issues/Driving-growth/Middle-class-growth-in-emerging-markets---China-and-India-tomorrow-s-middle-classes |archive-date=4 March 2016 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is estimated that average real wages will quadruple between 2013 and 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/average-wages-in-india-could-quadruple-by-2030-pwc-report/article5186360.ece|title=Average wages in India could quadruple by 2030: PwC report|work=thehindu.com}}</ref>

The standard of living in India shows large disparity. For example, there is widespread poverty in rural areas of India, where medical care tends to be very basic or unavailable, while cities boast of world class medical establishments. Similarly, the very latest machinery may be used in some construction projects, but many construction workers work without mechanisation in most projects.<ref>[http://www.sewaresearch.org/pdf/researches/labouring_brick_by_brick.pdf Labouring Brick by Brick: A Study of Construction Workers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100705011010/http://www.sewaresearch.org/pdf/researches/labouring_brick_by_brick.pdf |date=5 July 2010 }} - www.sewa.org</ref> However, a rural middle class is now emerging in India, with some rural areas seeing increasing prosperity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/487357/rural-areas-see-middle-class.html|title=Rural areas see middle class rise|website=Deccan Herald}}</ref>

In 2010, the per capita PPP-adjusted GDP for [[India]] was US$3,608.<ref>[[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita]]</ref>

== Poverty ==
{{Main|Poverty in India}}
24.3% of the population earned less than US$1 (PPP, around US$0.25 in nominal terms) a day in 2005, down from 42.1% in 1981.<ref name="WorldBankPoverty">{{cite web|url=http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&piPK=64165421&theSitePK=469372&menuPK=64166093&entityID=000158349_20080826113239|title=The developing world is poorer than we thought, but no less successful in the fight against poverty|publisher=World Bank|year=2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323214139/http://econ.worldbank.org/external/default/main?pagePK=64165259&piPK=64165421&theSitePK=469372&menuPK=64166093&entityID=000158349_20080826113239|archivedate=23 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="business-standard.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/storypage.php?autono=332669|title=India has fewer poor people: World Bank|publisher=Business Standard}}</ref> 41.6% of its population (540 million people approx.) is living below the new international poverty line of $1.25 (PPP) per day, down from 59.8% in 1981.<ref name="WorldBankPoverty"/> The World Bank further estimates that a third of the global poor now reside in India.

On the other hand, the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]] of India uses its own criteria and has estimated that 27.5% of the population was living below the [[poverty line]] in 2004–2005, down from 51.3% in 1977–1978, and 36% in 1993-1994.<ref>[http://www.planningcommission.gov.in/news/prmar07.pdf Poverty estimates for 2004-05], Planning commission, [[Government of India]], March 2007. Accessed: 25 August 2007</ref> The source for this was the 61st round of the National Sample Survey (NSS) and the criterion used was monthly per capita consumption expenditure below {{INR}}&nbsp;356.35 for rural areas and {{INR}}&nbsp;538.60 for urban areas. 75% of the poor are in rural areas, most of them are [[wage|daily wagers]], self-employed householders and landless labourers.

Although Indian economy has grown steadily over the last two decades, its growth has been uneven when comparing different social groups, economic groups, geographic regions, and rural and urban areas.<ref name="World bank 2006">{{cite web |url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/SOUTHASIAEXT/Resources/DPR_FullReport.pdf |format=PDF|title=Inclusive Growth and Service delivery: Building on India’s Success |publisher=[[World Bank]]|year=2006 |accessdate=28 April 2007}}</ref> For the year 2015-16, the GSDP growth rates of [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Bihar]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]] was higher than [[Maharashtra]], [[Odisha]] or [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AP stands 1st in India in GSDP growth rate |url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/AP-stands-1st-in-India-in-GSDP-growth-rate/articleshow/52709609.cms |publisher =[[The Times of India]] |accessdate =13 April 2017}}</ref>

Since the early 1950s, successive governments have implemented various schemes, under [[Planned economy|planning]], to alleviate poverty, that have met with partial success. Programmes like ''Food for work'' and ''National Rural Employment Programme'' have attempted to use the unemployed to generate productive assets and build rural infrastructure.<ref name="survey">{{cite web|title=Economic Survey 2004–2005|url=http://indiabudget.nic.in/es2004-05/esmain.htm| accessdate = 15 July 2006}}</ref> In August 2005, the [[Parliament of India|Indian parliament]] passed the ''Rural Employment Guarantee Bill'', the largest programme of this type, in terms of cost and coverage, which promises 100 days of minimum wage employment to every rural household in 200 of [[Districts of India|India's 600 districts]]. <!---ani-REGB---> The Indian government is planning to bring in more economic reforms which can help farmers and unskilled labourers transition into industrialised sectors.

{{see also|List of Indian states by life expectancy at birth}}

== Physical infrastructure ==
{{Main|Transport in India|Water supply and sanitation in India}}
[[Image:DelhiMetro.jpg|thumb|right|Pictured here, is the [[New Delhi Metro]], operational since 2002 and seen as a model for other metros.]]
Since independence, India has allocated nearly half of the total outlay of the five-year plans for [[infrastructure|infrastructural]] development. Much of the total outlay was spent on large projects in the area of irrigation, energy, transport, communications and social overheads. Development of infrastructure was completely in the hands of the public sector and was plagued by corruption, bureaucratic inefficiencies, urban-bias and an inability to scale investment.<ref name="infra">{{cite book | author=Sankaran, S | title=Indian Economy: Problems, Policies and Development | publisher=Margham Publications | year=1994 | id=ISBN}}</ref>
Calcutta city was the first city in India to boast of a metro-system. 
India's low spending on power, construction, transportation, telecommunications and [[real estate]], at $31 billion or 6% of GDP in 2002 has prevented India from sustaining a growth rate of around 8%. This has prompted the government to partially open up infrastructure to the private sector allowing foreign investment.<ref name="cnn-infra">{{cite news | title=Infrastructure the missing link | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/asiapcf/09/03/india.eye.infra/ | accessdate=14 August 2005 | work=CNN | date=6 October 2004}}</ref><ref name="asiatradehub-infra">{{cite web | title=Infrastructure in India: Requirements and favorable climate for foreign investment | url=http://www.asiatradehub.com/india/intro.asp | accessdate=14 August 2005 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050713073856/http://www.asiatradehub.com/india/intro.asp | archivedate=13 July 2005 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> India holds second position in the world in roadways' construction.<ref name="Road">{{cite web | title=Infrastructure Rankings | url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2085rank.html}}</ref>

As of 31 December 2005, there were an estimated 835,000 broadband lines in India.<ref name="Broadband">{{cite web | title=World broadband statistics q4-2005 | url=http://www.point-topic.com/contentDownload/dslanalysis/world%20broadband%20statistics%20q4%202005.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate=24 July 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060705053249/http://www.point-topic.com/contentDownload/dslanalysis/world%20broadband%20statistics%20q4%202005.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 5 July 2006}}</ref> Low tele-density is the major hurdle for slow pick-up in broadband services. Over 76% of the broadband lines were via DSL and the rest via cable modems.

A 2007 study by the Asian Development Bank showed that in 20 cities the average duration of water supply was only 4.3 hours per day. No city had a continuous water supply. The longest duration of supply was 12 hours per day in [[Chandigarh]], and the lowest was 0.3 hours per day in [[Rajkot]].<ref name=ADB2007>{{cite book|title=2007 Benchmarking and Data Book of Water Utilities in India|date=2007|publisher=[[Asian Development Bank]]|isbn=978-971-561-648-5|page=3|url=http://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/27970/2007-indian-water-utilities-data-book.pdf}}</ref>

A study by [[WaterAid]] estimated as many as 157 million Indian or 41 percent of Indians living in urban areas, live without adequate sanitation. India comes top for having the greatest number of
urbanites living without sanitation. India tops urban sanitation crisis, has the largest amount of urban dwellers without sanitation and the most open defecators over 41 million people.<ref>{{cite web | title=The State of the World’s Toilet 2016| url=http://wateraidindia.in/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/Overflowing-cities-The-State-of-the-Worlds-Toilets-2016.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Overflowing Cities: 157 Million Indians Still Without Toilets| url=https://international.thenewslens.com/article/55250| accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>

== Regional imbalance ==
{{Main|List of regions of India}}
One of the critical problems facing India's economy is the sharp and growing regional variations among India's different states and territories in terms of per capita income, poverty, availability of infrastructure and socio-economic development. For instance, the difference in growth rate between the [[States of India by size of economy|forward and backward states]] was 0.3% (5.2% & 4.9%) during 1980–81 to 1990–91, but had grown to 3.3% (6.3% & 3.0%) during 1990–91 to 1997–98.<ref name="Datt-13">{{cite book |author1=Datt, Ruddar  |author2=Sundharam, K.P.M.  |lastauthoramp=yes | title=Indian Economy | pages = 471–472 | chapter = 27}}</ref>

The five-year plans have attempted to reduce regional disparities by encouraging industrial development in the interior regions, but industries still tend to concentrate around urban areas and port cities. Even the industrial townships in the interiors, [[Bhilai]] for instance, resulted in very little development in the surrounding areas.<ref name="bharadwaj-1">{{cite book | author=Bharadwaj, Krishna | year=1991 | chapter = Regional differentiation in India | editor=Sathyamurthy, T.V. | title = Industry & agriculture in India since independence | pages=189–199 | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=0-19-564394-1}}</ref> After liberalisation, the disparities have grown despite the efforts of the union government in reducing them. Part of the reason being that manufacturing and services and not agriculture are the engines of growth. The more advanced states are better placed to benefit from them, with infrastructure like well developed ports, urbanisation and an educated and skilled workforce which attract manufacturing and service sectors. The union and state governments of backward regions are trying to reduce the disparities by offering tax holidays, cheap land, etc., and focusing more on sectors like tourism, which although being geographically and historically determined, can become a source of growth and is faster to develop than other sectors.<ref name="understanding-2">{{cite journal |author1=Sachs, D. Jeffrey |author2=Bajpai, Nirupam |author3=Ramaiah, Ananthi |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Understanding Regional Economic Growth in India |year=2002 |version=Working paper 88 |url=http://www2.cid.harvard.edu/cidwp/088.pdf |format=PDF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701042205/http://www2.cid.harvard.edu/cidwp/088.pdf |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name="planning-2">{{cite web | author=Kurian, N.J. | title=Regional disparities in india | work= | url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/reports/sereport/ser/vision2025/regdsprty.doc | accessdate=6 August 2005 }}</ref>
